# The For-Sale Market {#sec-market-ownership}

<!-- Purpose: ownership-market dynamics — prices, payments, inventory, and buyer affordability for the study area (PLAN.md §7 Ch 3a).
     Narrative rule: takeaway titles + bullet findings + callouts only — no drafted prose. -->



## Sales volume


::: {.cell layout-align="left"}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Home sales cooled sharply from the 2020–21 peak](market-ownership_files/figure-html/fig-sales-volume-1.png){#fig-sales-volume fig-align='left' fig-alt='Column chart of Fauquier County annual home sales from 2016 to 2026. Volume climbs from about 1,067 in 2016 to a 2020–21 peak near 1,450–1,470, then falls to roughly 850–940 sales a year in 2022–2025. Columns through 2021 come from the earlier GP/VAR series and 2022 onward from Bright MLS; the final 2026 column is a partial year-to-date count.' width=100%}
:::
:::


- Sales peaked at **1,466 in 2021** and have since fallen to **938 in 2025 — down about 36%** from the pandemic-era high.
- The cooling reflects **thin supply and higher financing costs**, not falling demand — prices kept climbing through the slowdown (@fig-price-trend).
- Counts through 2021 come from the GP/VAR annual series and 2022 onward from Bright MLS; **2026 is a partial year-to-date count** and is not comparable to the full years.

::: {.callout-note}
## A note on sales counts
Bright MLS's **published monthly summary** reports roughly **20% more sales** than the transaction-level export used for the volume series above (e.g. 1,127 vs 938 closings in 2025) — a near-constant level offset across every year, consistent with a property-type filter on the export. **Median sale prices agree between the two sources to within ~0.1%**, so the price findings are unaffected; the *level* of sales counts (and the active-listing snapshot below) should be read as the export's narrower definition, while the year-over-year *trend* holds under either source.
:::

## Prices


::: {.cell layout-align="left"}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Prices climbed steeply — and kept rising even after inflation](market-ownership_files/figure-html/fig-price-trend-1.png){#fig-price-trend fig-align='left' fig-alt='Line chart of Fauquier County median sold price from 2016 to 2025. The nominal monthly line rises from about $360,000 to $650,000; the inflation-adjusted line in 2025 dollars rises more gently from about $465,000 to $650,000. Two annual town-ZIP lines beginning in 2022 sit on either side of the county: Warrenton near $690,000 and Bealeton near $570,000 by 2025.' width=100%}
:::
:::


- The county's **median sold price nearly doubled in nominal terms — about $360k (2016) to $650k (2025), +81%**.
- Even after inflation, **real prices rose from roughly $465k to $650k in 2025 dollars (+40%)** — genuine appreciation, not just inflation.
- The town ZIPs track the county: **Warrenton (~$690k in 2025) runs above Bealeton (~$570k)**. Town-ZIP series begin in 2022 because the county's 2016–2021 monthly series is VAR (county-only).

## Prices vs. payments vs. incomes


::: {.cell layout-align="left"}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Monthly mortgage payments have far outrun both prices and incomes](market-ownership_files/figure-html/fig-price-payment-income-1.png){#fig-price-payment-income fig-align='left' fig-alt='Indexed line chart set to 100 in 2016 for Fauquier County. The monthly mortgage payment line rises fastest, reaching about 250 by 2025; the median sold price line reaches about 180; and median household income rises most slowly to about 145 by 2024. The gap between payments and incomes widens sharply after 2021 as mortgage rates jump.' width=100%}
:::
:::


- Over 2016–2025 the **median price rose +81%, but the monthly payment on that home rose +152%** — the 30-year rate climbed from 2.9566667% (2021) to 6.5966667% (2025), compounding the price increase.
- **Median household income rose only +43% through 2024** — far behind both, so buying power has fallen sharply.
- The pattern matches the GP study's Figure 9 direction (GP: price +79%, payment +127%, income +35%); FHFH's actuals run somewhat higher on all three but tell the same story — **payments ≫ prices ≫ incomes**.

## Price segments


::: {.cell layout-align="left"}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![The entry-level segment has all but disappeared](market-ownership_files/figure-html/fig-price-bands-1.png){#fig-price-bands fig-align='left' fig-alt='Hundred-percent stacked column chart of Fauquier County home sales by price band from 2022 to 2026. The under-$250,000 band shrinks from about 4% to under 2%, and the $250,000–$350,000 band from about 10% to 4%, while the $500,000–$750,000 and $750,000-plus bands together grow to roughly three-quarters of all sales.' width=100%}
:::
:::


- **Homes under $250k fell from 3.8% of sales in 2022 to 1.6% in 2025**; everything under $350k is now barely 6% of the market.
- The **$750k+ band has surged to 35% of sales** (from 21% in 2022), and the modal band is now **$500–750k** (41%).
- This is the tail end of a long collapse: the GP study found under-$250k sales fell from **27.8% (2016) to 3.0% (2021)** — the MLS-only view here (2022+) shows the entry level eroding the rest of the way.

## Days on market & supply


::: {.cell layout-align="left"}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Homes still sell fast, but with a pronounced seasonal rhythm](market-ownership_files/figure-html/fig-days-on-market-1.png){#fig-days-on-market fig-align='left' fig-alt='Line chart of median days to sell for Fauquier County home sales, monthly from 2022 to mid-2026. A faint monthly line swings between roughly 5 days in spring and 30 to 40 days in winter each year; a heavier three-month average line makes the seasonal sawtooth clear and drifts modestly higher in 2025 before easing in 2026.' width=100%}
:::
:::


- Homes sell **fast — a median of 10–11 days in 2022–2024, rising to 21 in 2025** as higher rates cooled demand, but still weeks, not months.
- The monthly view exposes a **strong seasonal rhythm the annual averages hide**: listings linger roughly 25–40 days in December–February and sell in under 10 by spring, every year.


::: {.cell layout-align="left"}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Inventory has loosened from its pandemic lows — but supply is still tight](market-ownership_files/figure-html/fig-supply-trend-1.png){#fig-supply-trend fig-align='left' fig-alt='Two-panel chart for 2022 to mid-2026. The top panel shows active listings rising from about 315 to a 2025 peak above 450 in Fauquier County, with Warrenton flat near 45; the bottom panel shows months of supply climbing from about 3 to roughly 4 to 5 months for both the county and Warrenton, staying below the dashed six-month line that marks a balanced market.' width=100%}
:::
:::


- Active for-sale inventory has climbed from a tight **~315 listings a month in 2022 to ~392 in 2025**, and months of supply from about **3.4 to 4.3 months** — a real loosening from the pandemic-era squeeze.
- Even so, supply stays **well below the roughly six-month mark** that separates a seller's from a buyer's market: Fauquier remains a seller's market, just a less extreme one than at the 2021–22 peak.

::: {.callout-note}
## Inventory is recovering, not recovered
Contrary to a point-in-time reading, the monthly Bright MLS series shows active listings and months of supply **trending upward since 2022** (from ~3.4 to ~4.3 months) as higher rates slowed the frantic pace — but Fauquier is **still firmly a seller's market**, with supply short of the ~6-month balance point and homes selling within weeks for most of the year.
:::

## What it takes to buy


::: {.cell layout-align="left"}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Buying the median home takes about $60,000 more than the median household earns](market-ownership_files/figure-html/fig-income-to-buy-1.png){#fig-income-to-buy fig-align='left' fig-alt='Two-bar comparison for Fauquier County. The income needed to afford the median-priced home is about $190,600, well above the actual median household income of about $130,200 — a gap of roughly $60,000.' width=100%}
:::
:::


- Affording the **$650k median home requires about $190,586** in household income under standard underwriting — versus Fauquier's actual **$130,189** median, a gap of roughly **$60,000**.
- The gap is driven by the same forces as @fig-price-payment-income: high prices *and* a 6.49% mortgage rate.
- This figure reuses the affordability parameters from the gaps analysis so Chapters 3 and 4 reconcile; the full owner/renter gap by income band is developed in @sec-gaps.

## What the interviews said vs. what the data shows

::: {.callout-important}
## Interview validation

- **"Only about 3 for-sale listings under $350,000 were on the market (April 2026)."** *Confirmed.* The July 2026 listing export shows **exactly 3 of 218 active listings priced under $350,000** (@fig-price-bands) — the entry-level for-sale segment has effectively vanished. (The 218-listing export is the narrower property-type subset noted above; Bright MLS's published count for the county runs higher, but the near-total absence of sub-$350k inventory holds regardless.)
- **"Homes are expensive relative to what local incomes can support."** *Confirmed and nuanced.* Median prices nearly doubled since 2016 and rose in real terms (@fig-price-trend); the income needed to buy the median home now exceeds the actual median by ~$60k (@fig-income-to-buy). The squeeze is amplified by financing: monthly payments rose far faster than prices or incomes (@fig-price-payment-income).
- **"Buyers face a quality-versus-price mismatch — what's affordable isn't desirable, and what's desirable isn't affordable."** *Confirmed and nuanced.* New construction skews larger and pricier (@sec-inventory), the sub-$350k segment has all but disappeared (@fig-price-bands), and the market still moves fast (@fig-days-on-market) — leaving entry-level buyers with few options at any quality level.
:::
